<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880308-0068 </DOCNO><HL> Army Awards $1 Billion Job On Data Systems </HL><SO> </SO><CO> MD LIT TXT CGP RTN </CO><IN> ARO </IN><G> DEF </G><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Science Applications International Corp. received an Army contract estimated at $1 billion to develop and maintain an information system for hospitals.    The huge computer system, to be built over eight years, would support the Defense Department's international network of health-care facilities by storing patient information and assisting communication within the military health-care system.    Science Applications International is a closely held defense and environmental technologies concern based in La Jolla, Calif. For the fiscal year ended Jan. 31, 1987, it had sales of about $690 million.    In other awards yesterday, McDonnell Douglas Corp. received a $130 million Air Force contract for F-15E aircraft production.    Litton Industries Inc. won a $24.3 million Army contract for electronic equipment.    Units of Textron Inc. were awarded Army contracts totaling $21.6 million for Stinger missile systems for OH-58C helicopters and engines for AH-1S helicopters.    Coastal Eagle Point Oil Co., a unit of Coastal Corp., received a $15.5 million Defense Logistics Agency contract for jet fuel.    Raytheon Co. was issued a $14.6 million Army contract to develop weapon-control technologies for an electromagnetic gun. </TEXT></DOC>